<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-698-512  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 698 512.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Weekly  July 19 1990 n1223 p72(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Database makers calm user fears.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Flood, Gary.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Suppliers of relational databases are assuring users that theirproducts are safe from data loss.andP;  Some versions of the SQLstandard query language lose information when users update a file.andO;The bug happens when cursors are implemented as copies of datarather than pointers and when a database handles locking of dataas cursor stability rather than repeatable read.andP;  Users shouldprotect the data just read by locking it.andP;  Cincom, DEC, SoftwareAG, Unify and Informix claim their programs are safe from thepossibility of data loss.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Relational Data BasesProduct FailuresSystem IntegrityDebuggingStructured Query Language.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>